06454nam a22010575i 9789048524570DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485245707 a10.1515/97890485245702doi  a(DE-B1597)550868  a(OCoLC)1192499368  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aMED1160002bisacsh04a616.982231 aChen, Ajiang, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChinese "Cancer Villages" :bRural Development, Environmental Change and Public Health /cYajuan Luo, Pengli Cheng, Ajiang Chen. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Figures, Graphs and Tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tPreface to the English Language Edition -- t1 Retrospective Thoughts on the ‘Cancer Village’ Phenomenon -- t2 The Ins and Outs of a ‘Cancer Village’ -- t3 A Subei ‘Cancer Village’ -- t4 Environmental Change and Health Risks -- t5 A Prosperous ‘Cancer Village’ -- t6 Coexistence of Poverty and Cancer -- t7 Problematization and De-stigmatization -- t8 Behind the ‘High Incidence of Lung Cancer’ -- t9 Villagers’ Perceptions of and Responses to the Relationship between Cancer and Pollution -- t10 Villagers Strategies for Mitigating Environmental Health Risks -- tIndex -- tIndex (Chinese)0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the process of industrialization and urbanization, the phenomenon of cancer villages appears in many places of China. Although the relationship between pollution and cancer is hard to distinguish in most of those cancer villages, villagers, media and local government all agree that high incidence of cancer is related to environmental pollution, and especially and mostly with industrial pollution. Cancer villages already exist as a fact of social life and affect the lives of villagers, prompting action by government. The authors comprehensively analyse the relationship of cancer incidence, environmental pollution and lifestyle habits of villagers, drawing on sociological theory and method. They present the phenomenon of cancer villages in the particular current Chinese social, economic and cultural contexts and provide a wealth of informed analysis. It is of particular interest to those concerned with the impact of the environment on health.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCancer. 0aEnvironmental health. 0aEnvironmental toxicology. 0aMedical microbiology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aContemporary Society. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aEnvironment and Sustainability. 4aHealth and Medicine. 4aPolitics and Government. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aMEDICAL / Environmental Health.2bisacsh  aCancer Village.  aChina.  aEnvironment and Health.  aRisk Cognition.1 aAjiang, Chen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaihong, Li, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheng, Pengli, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHoldaway, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuo, Yajuan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPengli, Cheng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQi, Li, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWuyi, Wang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYajuan, Luo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068955608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG